2. `switch` statement is written _without_ `break` or `return`, therefore, `&quot;not valid&quot;` would be always returned after fixing the NPE
3. Only _three valid_ options should be generated and used in this rock-scissors-stone generator.

Possible fixes:
1. Use Java 12 `switch` expression syntax:
```java

public String computerChoice() {   
    return switch (new Random().nextInt(3)) {  // values in range [0..2]
        case 0 -&gt; &quot;paper&quot;;
        case 1 -&gt; &quot;rock&quot;;
        default -&gt; &quot;scissors&quot;; // the only remaining value 2 should be default
    }
} 
```
2. Use `return` in older `switch` statement:
```java
public String computerChoice() {   
    switch (new Random().nextInt(3)) {  // values in range [0..2]
        case 0: return &quot;paper&quot;;
        case 1: return &quot;rock&quot;;
        default: return &quot;scissors&quot;;
    }
} 
```

3. Create and use an array of possible values without any `switch` at all to reduce the code complexity:
```java
private static final String PRS = {&quot;paper&quot;, &quot;rock&quot;, &quot;scissors&quot;};

public String computerChoice() {   
    return PRS[new Random().nextInt(PRS.length)];
} 
