answers.body_markdown:
# Cause

MapStruct can not know whether you want to convert all Foo.bar objects into separate objects or just map an explicit one.

For example:
```
List&lt;Foobar&gt; convert(Foo[] foos);
```
Will attempt to use a mapping method `Foobar convert(Foo foo)` and not `Foobar convert(Foo foo, Foo.Bar bar)`.

For collections you can expect that the input size equals the output size with mapstruct. So 5 Foo objects should result into 5 FooBar objects, if you want it to increase you will have to write some manual code for this, see below.

# Solution

What mapstruct does support is setting up the mapping at the detailed level, and then you need to manually call it.

For example:

```
@Mapping(target = &quot;a&quot;, source = &quot;foo.a&quot;)
@Mapping(target = &quot;b&quot;, source = &quot;bar.b&quot;)
Foobar convert( Foo foo, Foo.Bar bar );

default List&lt;Foobar&gt; convert( Foo[] foos ) {
  List&lt;Foobar&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
  for ( Foo foo : foos ) {
    for ( Foo.Bar bar : foo.bar ) {
      result.add( convert( foo, bar ) );
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

using the more complex example:
```
@Mapping(target = &quot;id&quot;, source = &quot;a.id&quot;)
@Mapping(target = &quot;date&quot;, source = &quot;b.d&quot;)
@Mapping(target = &quot;number&quot;, source = &quot;c.i&quot;)
@Mapping(target = &quot;text&quot;, source = &quot;d.s&quot;)
Result convert( A a, B b, C c, D d );

default List&lt;Result&gt; convert( A[] as ) {
  List&lt;Result&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
  for ( A a : as ) {
    for ( A.B b : a.b ) {
      for ( A.C c : b.c ) {
        for ( A.D d : c.d ) {
          result.add( convert( a, b, c, d ) );
        }
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

